"Kaser G., Hardy D.R., Mölg T., Bradley R.S., Hyera T.M.","Modern glacier retreat on Kilimanjaro as evidence of climate change: Observations and facts",2004,"International Journal of Climatology","24","3",,"329","339",,,10.1002/joc.1008,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-1842843637&partnerID=40&md5=93f4df718e4384893c20d31181b15269","Tropical Glaciology Group, Department of Geography, University of Innsbruck, Innrain 52, Innsbruck A-6020, Austria; Climate System Research Center, Department of Geosciences, University of Massachusetts, Amherst, MA 01003-9297, United States; Tanzania Meteorological Agency, P.O. Box 3056, Dar es Salaam, Tanzania","Kaser, G., Tropical Glaciology Group, Department of Geography, University of Innsbruck, Innrain 52, Innsbruck A-6020, Austria; Hardy, D.R., Climate System Research Center, Department of Geosciences, University of Massachusetts, Amherst, MA 01003-9297, United States; Mölg, T., Tropical Glaciology Group, Department of Geography, University of Innsbruck, Innrain 52, Innsbruck A-6020, Austria; Bradley, R.S., Climate System Research Center, Department of Geosciences, University of Massachusetts, Amherst, MA 01003-9297, United States; Hyera, T.M., Tanzania Meteorological Agency, P.O. Box 3056, Dar es Salaam, Tanzania","In recent years, Kilimanjaro and its vanishing glaciers have become an 'icon' of global warming, attracting broad interest. In this paper, a synopsis of (a) field observations made by the authors and (b) climatic data as reported in the literature (proxy and long-term instrumental data) is presented to develop a new concept for investigating the retreat of Kilimanjaro's glaciers, based on the physical understanding of glacier-climate interactions. The concept considers the peculiarities of the mountain and implies that climatological processes other than air temperature control the ice recession in a direct manner. A drastic drop in atmospheric moisture at the end of the 19th century and the ensuing drier climatic conditions are likely forcing glacier retreat on Kilimanjaro. Future investigations using the concept as a governing hypothesis will require research at different climatological scales. © 2004 Royal Meteorological Society.","Climate change; Data synopsis; Glaciological field observations; Kilimanjaro; Research concept; Tropical glaciers","Data acquisition; Glacial geology; Glaciers; Global warming; Ice; Moisture; Climatological processes; Ice recession; Climatology; air temperature; atmospheric moisture; climate change; glacier retreat; Africa; East Africa; Kilimanjaro [Kilimanjaro (RGN)]; Kilimanjaro [Tanzania]; Sub-Saharan Africa; Tanzania",,,,,,"Basalirwa, C.P.K., Odiyo, J.O., Mingodo, R.J., Mpeta, E.J., The climatological regions of Tanzania based on the rainfall characteristics (1999) International Journal of Climatology, 19, pp. 69-80; Black, E., Slingo, J., Sperber, K.R., An observational study of the relationship between excessively strong short rains in coastal East Africa and Indian Ocean SST (2003) Monthly Weather Review, 131, pp. 74-94; Bonnefille, R., Chalié, F., Pollen-inferred precipitation time-series from equatorial mountains, Africa, the last 40kyr BP (2000) Global and Planetary Change, 26, pp. 25-50; Broecker, W.S., Mountain glaciers: Records of atmospheric water vapor content? (1997) Global Biogeochemical Cycles, 4, pp. 589-597; Coutts, H.H., Rainfall of the Kilimanjaro area (1969) Weather, 24, pp. 66-69; Downie, C., Wilkinson, P., (1972) The Geology of Kilimanjaro, , Department of Geology, Sheffield University: Sheffield; Eskridge, R.E., Adduchov, O.A., Chernykh, I.V., Panmao, Z., Polansky, A.C., Doty, S.R., A comprehensive aerological reference data set (CARDS): Rough and systematic errors (1995) Bulletin of the American Meteorological Society, 76, pp. 1759-1776; Francou, B., Vuille, M., Wagnon, P., Mendoza, J., Sicart, J.E., Tropical climate change recorded by a glacier in the central Andes during the last decades of the 20th cent